The Scottish TV writer/producer, best known for “Sherlock” and “Doctor Who,” has turned to “Dracula” for his next work.
But things like Dracula or Sherlock Holmes — these are characters that have fascinated people for over a century.
Moffat, who co-created “Dracula” with his “Sherlock” writing partner Mark Gatiss, said the idea originated while they were making the Emmy-winning “Sherlock” (which made Benedict Cumberbatch a star and aired from 2010 to 2017).
When we cast Benedict [Cumberbatch] as Sherlock Holmes, he could sort of own the role because at that point he had no other associations,” he says.
“He just sort of became Sherlock Holmes for a while.